Product Version     25.10    Cadence Design Systems, Inc.
editCutWire(25.10)                                          editCutWire(25.10)

Name
       editCutWire  -  Cuts wires, bus guides, or rectangles, such as physical
       pin port shapes, at the specified location

Syntax
       editCutWire

       [-help]

       [-only_visible_wires]

       [-selected]

       {-lines {<x1 y1 x2 y2 ...>} | [-box {x1 y1 x2 y2}  [-delete_wire_in_box
       ]] }

       Cuts  wires,  bus  guides,  or  rectangles,  such  as physical pin port
       shapes, at the specified location. You can choose to cut by line (using
       the -lines parameter) or by box (using the -box parameter.  editCutWire
       honors setEditMode -cut_wire_overlap settings.

       Patch wires are also supported.

Parameters
       -help  Prints a brief description that includes type and default infor-
              mation for each editCutWire parameter.

              For a detailed description of the command and all of its parame-
              ters, use the man command:

              man editCutWire

       -box {<x1 y1 x2 y2>}
              Specifies  the lower-left and upper-right coordinates of the box
              for cutting wires, bus guides, or rectangles.

              The -box option currently has the following limitations:

              * The cut-box must be a rectangle (or square). A  polygon  shape
                will be ignored.

              * Only  the wires that are perpendicular to the cut-box edge are
                cut. In addition, the cut-box edge must pass across the  wire,
                bus guide, or rectangle completely.

              * This  option  can  be used to cut only horizontal and vertical
                wires. 45-degree wires are not yet supported.

       -delete_wire_in_box
              Deletes automatically the cut wires in the area  specified  with
              -box.  This  option  can be specified only if -box is specified.
              Otherwise, the tool returns an error.

       -lines {<x1 y1 x2 y2 ...>}
              Specifies the start and end coordinates of one or more line seg-
              ments for cutting wires, bus guides, or rectangles.

              If you specify multiple cut-line segments, they should be paral-
              lel to each other. For instance, you cannot specify one horizon-
              tal cut-line and one vertical cut-line with the  -lines  parame-
              ter. If you do, the tool reports the following error:

              Cut lines are not parallel.

              In  addition, a cut-line must cut across the wire, bus guide, or
              rectangle from one edge to the other. Once cut, the signal  wire
              pieces  maintain  a one-half wire-width extension. Special wires
              do not maintain an extension.

              When you run editCutWire, the tool snaps  the  cut-line  to  the
              manufacturing  grid  automatically. The change in coordinates is
              displayed at the prompt as a warning such as follows:

              WARNING: Cut-line is auto-snapped from  (966.343500  1227.245500
              966.811500  1227.245500)  to  (966.345000 1227.245000 966.810000
              1227.245000).

              Note that the tool records only the cut-line  coordinate  before
              snapping in the log file.

              Note:  The -lines option supports editing of 45-degree wire seg-
              ments.

              In addition, you can also draw a 45-degree  cut-line  to  cut  a
              group of wires in a stair pattern as shown below:

              Both  regular and special wires can be cut with a 45-degree cut-
              line. However, patch wires cannot be cut in this way.  When  you
              use a 45-degree cut-line, the wires are cut from the touch point
              of  the  center line. You can use a single 45-degree cut-line to
              cut wires in different directions as shown below:

       -only_visible_wires
              Specifies that only the wires on the visible layers are cut.  If
              this  parameter  is  not  specified, the tool cuts all the wires
              overlapping with the cut-line or box.

       -selected
              Specifies that only the selected wires, bus guides,  or  rectan-
              gles should be cut.

Examples
              * The  following command cuts the wires through which the speci-
                fied cut-line passes:

                editCutWire -lines {200 300 200 310}

              *

                Consider the wire depicted below:

                The following command  cuts  the  wire,  along  the  specified
                45-degree cut-line segments, {95.30 -641.16 95.39 -641.08} and
                {95.69 -641.17 95.78 -641.08}:

                editCutWire  -lines {95.30 -641.16 95.39 -641.08 95.69 -641.17
                95.78 -641.08}

              * The following diagrams show examples of using a cut-box to cut
                wires:

                * In a), the horizontal wire is cut. The vertical wire is  not
                  cut  because the cut-box edges that are perpendicular to the
                  wire do not pass through it completely.

                * In b), both the horizontal and vertical wires are cut.

                * In c), the vertical wire is cut at tje two places where  the
                  perpendicular  edges  of  the  cut-box  pass through it com-
                  pletely. The horizontal wire is not cut.

                * In d), the horizontal wire is cut. The 45-degree wire is not
                  cut because 45-degree wire edits are not yet supported while
                  cutting by box.

                * In e), no cuts are made.

